CREATE TABLE products_partition_0 PARTITION OF products FOR VALUES WITH (modulus 10, remainder 0);
CREATE TABLE products_partition_1 PARTITION OF products FOR VALUES WITH (modulus 10, remainder 1);
-- ... more partitions up to 9 ...
Adding New Partitions
When you need more partitions, you can add them like this:

sql
Copy code
-- Adding new partitions
CREATE TABLE products_partition_10 PARTITION OF products FOR VALUES WITH (modulus 20, remainder 10);
CREATE TABLE products_partition_11 PARTITION OF products FOR VALUES WITH (modulus 20, remainder 11);
-- ... more partitions as needed ...
Steps to Add Partitions
Determine the Need: Monitor the distribution and size of your partitions. If certain partitions become too large, it’s time to add more.
Create New Partitions: Use the CREATE TABLE ... PARTITION OF command to define new partitions.
Redistribute Data (if necessary): If existing partitions need to be rebalanced, you may need to redistribute data across the new partitions. This could involve some data migration.
Automation and Tools
To ease the management of partitions, you can:

Write Scripts: Create SQL scripts to automate the process of adding new partitions.
Use Tools: Some database management tools and extensions help manage partitioning in PostgreSQL.
Example: Monitoring and Maintenance Script
A simple script to check partition sizes and alert when a threshold is reached could be implemented. For example:

